{"title_page": "Lightvessels in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{For|lighthouses|List of lighthouses in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\nThe history of '''lightvessels in the United Kingdom''' goes back over 250 years. This page also gives a list of [[lightvessel]] stations within the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Channel Islands]] and [[Gibraltar]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe world's first lightvessel was the result of a business partnership between Robert Hamblin, an impoverished former [[barber]] and ship manager from [[King's Lynn]], and David Avery, a regular investor in small projects.<ref name=naish>Naish, J. M. ''Seamarks: Their History and Development'', Stanford Maritime, 1985, {{ISBN|978-0-540-07309-2}}, p. 107</ref> In 1730 the pair secured a government licence to moor a ship {{ndash}} with a prominent light affixed to it to serve as a navigation aid {{ndash}} at the [[Nore]] in the [[Thames]] mouth. Hamblin and Avery intended to profit from the vessel by collecting a fee from passing merchant vessels. The licence was opposed by [[Trinity House]] which considered that it possessed a monopoly on construction and maintenance of navigation aids in British waters. After extensive legal dispute the licence was revoked in 1732 and Trinity House assumed direct responsibility for the proposed lightship; Hamblin and Avery were granted nominal lease revenues in exchange.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Nautical Magazine and Naval Chronicle for 1865|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=624|year=2013|isbn=9781108054911}}</ref> The Nore lightship commenced operations in 1734.<ref name=Marcus>{{cite book|last=Marcus|first=G.J.|title=Heart of Oak: A Survey of British Sea Power in the Georgian Era|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1975|pages=[https://archive.org/details/heartofoaksurvey0000marc/page/53 53\u201354]|isbn=0192158120|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/heartofoaksurvey0000marc/page/53}}</ref>\n\nA further lightvessel was placed at the Dudgeon station, off the [[Norfolk]] coast, in 1736, with others following at [[Owers Bank]] (1788) and the [[Goodwin Sands]] (1793).<ref name=Marcus/> Many others were commissioned during the nineteenth century, especially off England's east coast and the approaches to the Thames, where there were many treacherous [[shoal]]s.\n\n[[File:Lv-Nore.jpg|thumb|right|Lightship LV86, on station at the Nore from 1931 to 1974]]\n\nFollowing their acquisition of the patent, all English and Welsh lightvessels were maintained by Trinity House, with the exception of the four vessels in the approaches to the [[River Mersey]], which were maintained by the [[Mersey Docks and Harbour Board]] until 1973, and those in the [[Humber Estuary]], which were the responsibility of the Humber Conservancy Board. In order to act as effective [[daymark]]s Trinity House lightvessels were painted red, with the station name in large white letters on the side of the hull, and a system of balls and cones at the masthead for identification. The first revolving light was fitted to the Swin Middle lightvessel in 1837: others used occulting or flashing lights. White lights were preferred for visibility though red and very occasionally green (as with the Mouse lightvessel) were also used.<ref name=miltoun>Miltoun, F. (ed) ''[http://www.kellscraft.com/ShipsandShipping/ShipsandShippingCh11.html Ships and Shipping]'', Moring Ltd, 1903, Ch. 11</ref>\n\n===Communications and safety===\n\nCommunication with lightvessels proved to be a major problem for Trinity House; lightvessel crews were well-placed to observe ships in distress, but could not always alert [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution|lifeboats]] on shore. After a series of shipwrecks, an experiment was conducted whereby a nine-mile undersea cable was run from the Sunk lightvessel in the [[Thames Estuary]] to the [[post office]] at [[Walton-on-the-Naze]]. This was intended to commence in 1884, but was plagued by delays;<ref name=hansard>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1884/may/16/board-of-trade-telegraphic-communication BOARD OF TRADE \u2014 TELEGRAPHIC COMMUNICATION WITH LIGHT VESSELS], [[Hansard]] 16-05-1884</ref> the trial was unsuccessful as the cable repeatedly broke. As a result of a motion brought forward by Sir [[Edward Birkbeck]], a [[Royal Commission]] was established to look at the issue of 'electrical communication' and gave its first Report in 1892;<ref name=hansard2>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1892/apr/26/coast-communications COAST COMMUNICATIONS], [[Hansard]] 26-04-1892</ref><ref name=hansard1>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1893/mar/21/communication-with-lighthouses COMMUNICATION WITH LIGHTHOUSES], [[Hansard]] 21-03-1893</ref> the East Goodwin lightvessel was used during one of [[Guglielmo Marconi]]'s early experiments in radio transmission in 1896.<ref name=marconi>{{cite book|last=Baker|first= W. J.|title=History of the Marconi Company|publisher= Routledge|year= 1998| ISBN= 978-0-415-14624-1|pages=39\u201340}}</ref> The world's first radio distress signal was transmitted by the East Goodwin lightvessel's radio operator on 17 March 1899, after the [[merchant vessel]] ''Elbe'' ran aground on the [[Goodwin Sands|Goodwins]], while on 30 April that year, the East Goodwin vessel transmitted a distress signal on its own behalf, when the [[SS]] ''R. F. Matthews'' rammed it in a dense fog. Safety was further improved by the development of more powerful lamps and through the replacement by [[foghorn]]s of the [[gong]]s previously used as fog signals.\n\n===Crew===\n\nUntil the later 20th century, all Trinity House vessels were permanently manned. An 1861 article in the [[Cornhill Magazine]] described lightshipmen as being paid 55 shillings a month (in addition to drawing 1 shilling and sixpence a week \"in lieu of 3 gallons of [[small beer|small-beer]]\"): the vessels were supplied, and the crews relieved, once a month. It was also noted that \"a general tone of decent, orderly and superior conduct\" was observed, that the men were \"very respectable [...] swearing and profane language are [...] prohibited\" and that every man was supplied with a Bible as well as \"a library of varied and entertaining literature\".<ref name=cornhill>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dbkCAAAAIAAJ Light-Vessels]'', The Cornhill Magazine, III (1861), 39.</ref>\n\nBy the start of the 20th century, Trinity House lightvessels had a crew of 11, of whom seven (a master and six ratings) would be on active duty at any one time. It was an extremely demanding and dangerous profession, and it would take 15 to 20 years of service to be promoted to master.<ref name=portcities1>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConNarrative.64/chapterId/1506/Trinity-House.html Trinity House], portcities.org, accessed 02-09-08</ref>\n\n===Replacement===\n\nThe majority of British lightvessels were decommissioned during the 1970s - 1980s and replaced with light floats or [[Lanby buoy|LANBY]] buoys, which were vastly cheaper to maintain: in 1974 at the time of Trinity House's original development project, lightship annual running costs at \u00a330,000 were ten times those of the LANBY.<ref name=design1974>Rowlands, D. [http://vads.ac.uk/diad/article.php?title=310&year=1974&article=d.310.39 \"Points of Reference\"], ''Design'' 310 (1974)</ref>\n\nThe remaining UK lightvessels have now been converted to unmanned operation and most now use [[solar power]].\n\n==Lightvessel stations==\n\nThe following are lightvessel ''stations''; i.e. a named position at which a lightvessel was placed, rather than the names of vessels themselves. Individual vessels were often transferred between different stations during their existence but they kept their Trinity House LV number. Stations themselves were occasionally changed, especially during wartime, when lights were only displayed in response to specific shipping needs. It is likely that photographs on various websites showing named lightvessels, may appear to be structurally different to comparable records on other web pages due to the fact that the particular LV might have been withdrawn from a station after photographing and being towed away for drydocking, overhaul and possible direction to a new station and therefore a different lightvessel would have been substituted at the named station on withdrawal of the previous LV. This has been most evident on those LVs that have been withdrawn and shipped to another port at home or abroad to become a floating museum, floating restaurant, 'clubhouse', etc. Scarweather LV and Helwick LV have for instance changed their r\u00f4le in their lifetime and their appearance on various records varies considerably.\n\n===England===\n\n====Active lightvessel stations====\n\nThe following are active stations at which Trinity House still maintains unmanned lightships, which also act as [[weather station]]s.\n\n[[File:Lightvessel East Goodwin.jpg|thumb|right|The East Goodwin lightvessel while under repair at [[Harwich]]]]\n\n*[[Channel Light Vessel Automatic|Channel Lightvessel]]  (north of [[Guernsey]])\n*F3 Lightvessel (middle of [[English Channel]], east of [[Ramsgate]])\n*East Goodwin Lightvessel ([[Goodwin Sands]])\n*[[Greenwich Light Vessel Automatic|Greenwich Lightvessel]]  (south of [[East Sussex]] on the [[Prime Meridian]])\n*[[Sandettie Light Vessel Automatic|Sandettie Lightvessel]]  (north of [[Calais]])\n*[[Sevenstones Lightship|Sevenstones Lightvessel]]  (west of [[Land's End]])\n*Sunk Lightvessel ([[Thames Estuary]])\n*[[Varne Bank|Varne Lightvessel]]  (southwest of [[Dover]])\n\n====Former lightvessel stations====\n[[File:Calshot Spit Lightship.jpg|thumb|Lightship LV78, formerly at [[Calshot Spit]] station]]\n\n*Bar ([[Mersey Estuary]]; maintained by MDHB)\n*Barrow Deep (Barrow Deep channel, Thames Estuary)\n*[[Black Deep]] (Thames Estuary)\n*Brake (Brake Sand, near [[Goodwin Sands]])\n*Bull (Bull Sands, mouth of the [[Humber Estuary]]; maintained by Humber Conservancy Board)\n*[[Calshot Spit]]\n*Cockle (North Sea)\n*Cork (Cork Bank, off [[Harwich]])\n*Corton (North Sea)\n*Crosby (Mersey Estuary; maintained by MDHB)\n*Docking Shoal, Norfolk coast\n*Inner / Outer Dowsing (North Sea; Inner Dowsing was the last manned lightship station, replaced by the Dowsing lighthouse in 1991)<ref name=dowsing>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConNarrative.64/chapterId/1506/Trinity-House.html Trinity House], portcities.org</ref>\n*Dudgeon (North Sea; the Dudgeon lightvessel was bombed by the [[Luftwaffe]] on 29 January 1940. Only one crew member, John Sanders, survived. The incident was the subject of a 1940 British Government [[propaganda]] film, ''[[Men of the Lightship]]''.<ref>{{Cite video  | people = David MacDonald (Director); Alberto Cavalcanti (Producer)  | title = Men of the Lightship    | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0309856/  | medium = Film (35mm, 24 mins, black & white)  | publisher = [[GPO Film Unit]]  | date = 1940}}</ref>\n*Edinburgh (Thames Estuary; the name refers to the Edinburgh Channel)\n*English and Welsh Grounds [[Bristol Channel]] (now a clubhouse in Bathurst Basin, Bristol)\n*Falls (Dover Strait)\n*Formby (Mersey Estuary, maintained by MDHB)\n*Galloper (Galloper shoal, North Sea)\n*Girdler (Thames Estuary)\n*Gull (marked the Gull Stream on the Goodwin Sands)- was rammed and sunk on 18 March 1929 by the City of York, resulting in the death of Captain Williams of the lightship. In 1947 it was bought for \u00a3750 by Thurrock Yacht Club, and towed to Grays to become the club\u2019s headquarters. It was last used as a clubhouse in 1971.The Gull was then abandoned and now suffers from regular acts of vandalism and degradation through river action.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thurrock Gazette|title=Landmark mast of Gull lightship is removed|url=http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/4361437.Landmark_mast_of_Gull_lightship_is_removed/|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref> \n*Gunfleet (Gunfleet Sands, Thames Estuary; replaced by [[Gunfleet Lighthouse]] in 1850)\n*Hasborough (North Sea)\n*Humber (maintained by Humber Conservancy Board)\n*[[Kentish Knock (England)|Kentish Knock]]\n*Knoll (Smith's Knoll, North Sea) off Norfolk\n*Leman and Ower (North Sea)\n*Longsand (Thames Estuary)\n*[[Morecambe Bay]]\n*Mouse (Mouse Sand, Thames Estuary)\n*Nab ([[Straits of Dover]]; replaced by the [[Nab Tower]] in 1920)\n*Newarp (North Sea)\n*[[Nore]] (Thames Estuary; the world's first manned lightship, 1731)\n*North [[Goodwin Sands|Goodwin]]\n*Northwestern (Mersey Estuary, maintained by MDHB)\n*Outer Gabbard (North Sea)\n*Owers ([[Owers Bank]], off [[Selsey Bill]]). Replaced with a beacon. (LV Owers now a wreck in [[Tel Aviv]] harbour)\n*Royal Sovereign (off [[Eastbourne]]; replaced with [[Royal Sovereign lighthouse]] 1971)\n*Shambles (the Shambles Bank, off [[Portland Bill]])\n*Shipwash (North Sea, off [[Harwich]])\n*South Goodwin lightvessel replaced the land based South Foreland Low lighthouse, also known as Old St Margaret's Lighthouse. On 25 October 1940, the South Goodwin Lightship was bombed by the Germans and sunk. The replacement lightvessel, LV90 sank on 27 November 1954 when cables to her two sea anchors broke in a hurricane-force storm, the worst storm in two centuries. The ship ran onto the Goodwin Sands close to the Keller Gut and turned on her side. The seven crew members perished, the only survivor being Ronald Murton an ornithologist from the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries. The wreck of the ship can still be seen at low tide. The next replacement ship was decommissioned and was towed away on 26 July 2006.<ref name=goodwin>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/conMediaFile.123/Crew-of-the-South-Goodwin-light-vessel.html South Goodwin Light Vessel], portcities.org</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trinityhousehistory.wordpress.com/tag/south-goodwin-lightvessel/|title=South Goodwin Lightvessel {{!}} Trinity House History|website=trinityhousehistory.wordpress.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1070066|desc=ST MARGARET'S OLD LIGHTHOUSE, St. Margaret's At Cliffe |accessdate=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n*Spurn ([[Spurn Head]]). Maintained by Humber Conservancy Board. A former [[Spurn Lightship|Spurn lightvessel]] is preserved at [[Hull Marina]].\n[[File:SFEC HULL .SPURN1.JPG|thumb|right|Preserved former Humber Conservancy Board ''Spurn'' lightvessel]]\n*Swin Middle (Swin Channel, Thames Estuary)\n*Tongue (Tongue Sands, Thames Estuary)\n*Lynn Well (entrance to [[The Wash]]); replaced with a [[Lanby buoy|LANBY]] (Large Automatic Navigation BuoY) September 1973\n*Would (North Sea)\n\n===Scotland, Isle of Man===\n\nLightvessels in Scotland and the Isle of Man were maintained by the [[Northern Lighthouse Board]], with the exception of one maintained by the Clyde Lighthouse Trust. Only the ''North Carr'' station was manned.\n\n*[[Bahama Bank]] (off [[Maughold Head]], [[Isle of Man]]; replaced by Maughold Head lighthouse 1914)\n*North Carr, [[Dundee]]\n*Otter Rock (south-west of the [[Isle of Mull]]).  Scottish Maritime Museum in Irving has a small scale coloured General Arrangement (1923) from Builder (Clyde Shipbuilding and Engineering Co. Ltd. hull #249, 60&nbsp;ft [183 m]).\n*Skeirinoe (Sgeir In-ao, near Scalpay, Harris)<ref>{{cite map|publisher  = [[Ordnance Survey]]|title = Map of Skeirinoe lightvessel (via National Library of Scotland maps API|url = http://nls.tileserver.com/?lat=57.84&lng=-6.55&zoom=13|edition = Popular Edition (Scotland)|year = 1920\u20131930|scale  = 1:253\u2009440|accessdate = 2011-08-13}}</ref>\n\n===Wales===\n\n[[File:Bateau feu Scarweather.jpg|thumb|Scarweather]]\nFormer Welsh lightships were maintained by Trinity House. Remaining substitute navigational aids still are.\n\n*Breaksea (off Barry (Breaksea Spit), Bristol Channel) Replaced by a LANBY, then a lightfloat and currently a lighted buoy with [[Radar beacon (racon)|RACON]] radar facility\n*Helwick (off [[Worms Head]])\n*[[Milford Haven (harbour)|Milford Haven Lightvessel]]\n*Scarweather ([[Swansea Bay]]; replaced with buoy 1989)\n*St Gowan (off Pembrokeshire coast). The station once carried the name St Govan, i.e., spelling change\n\n===Northern Ireland===\n*Petrel Lightvessel\n*South Rock Lightvessel\n\n==Decommissioned lightvessels==\nThe central records of the UK's light vessels were lost when Trinity House was bombed in 1940.\n\n*LV1; Light Vessel 1 was built in 1946 by [[Philip and Son|Philip & Son Ltd.]], [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]], England. In 1993 she was decommissioned and sold to Dean & Reddyhoff Ltd., [[Southampton]], for use as marina club house at Gosport, [[Hampshire]].<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV01/lv01gb.htm</ref>\n*LV3; Light Vessel 3 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. It sank off the coast of [[Israel]] in 2000.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160327090123/http://broadcasting-fleet.com/kingdavid2.htm</ref>\n*LV4; Light Vessel 4 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1989. In 1991 was sold to the Mus\u00e9e de Bateau in Douarnenez, [[France]], for \u00a340,000. She has been restored and renamed \"Scarweather\".<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV04/lv4gb.htm</ref>\n*LV5; Light Vessel 5 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. She was deployed as relief lightship to replace vessels undergoing refit or otherwise out of commission.  She served, among other stations, the South Goodwin in 1961, the Tongue in 1973, the Falls from 1973 to 1976 and the Varne in 1977.  Her last station was the South Goodwin again, before being withdrawn from service for conversion to unmanned operation.<ref>From text explaining the LV5's catoptric light system in the Maritime museum, Ramsgate, England.</ref>\n*LV8; Light Vessel 8 was built in 1949 by Philip & Son and decommissioned in 1991. In 2005 Radio Waddenzee bought the lightship and towed it from Rotterdam to Harlingen, [[Netherlands]], where she is used as a radio station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101022823/http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV08/lv08gb.htm|title=Trinity House lightvessel no. 8 - LV 8 - Radio Waddenzee - Jenni Baynton|date=1 January 2014|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n*LV11; [[Lightvessel No. 11|Light Vessel 11]] was built in 1951 by Philip & Son and decommissioned in 1988. She was saved from scrap and towed to the repair yard in the Waalhaven in Rotterdam, [[Netherlands]]. Rebuilt into a maritime restaurant.\n*LV12; [[Spurn Lightship|Light Vessel 12]] was constructed in 1927 by Goole Shipbuilding and Repairing Company Ltd., and decommissioned in 1975. After being acquired by the Hull City Council, since 1987, she has become a museum vessel in Hull Marina.\n*LV13; Light Vessel 13 was built in 1952 Philip & Son and transferred to Hamburg in 1991, where she was used as a restaurant and hotel.\n*LV14; [[Lightship 2000|Light Vessel 14]] was built in 1953 by Philip & Son, decommissioned in 1991, and opened in 2000 in [[Cardiff]] as a church ship. Works No.1246, it was removed from Cardiff docks on financial grounds on 18 May 2015 and towed to Sharpness for drydocking and refurbishment. The press had stated that it was to become a floating museum at Newnham in Gloucestershire and was reported as being seen there in August 2016. \n*LV15; Light Vessel 15 was built in 1954 by Philip & Son, sold in 1988 and is now used by a church charity Fellowship afloat near the river Blackwater in Essex.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV15/lv15gb.htm</ref>\n*LV16; Light Vessel 16 was built in 1954 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1988 and currently serves as the [[Sea Cadet Corps (United Kingdom)|Sea Cadets]] training ship TS Colne Light moored at the Hythe Quay in [[Colchester]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/1573/colne-light|title=Name Colne Light &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV18; Light Vessel 18 was built in 1958 by Philip & Son, sold in 1997, was used by pirate radio nostalgia stations (RSLs & BBC Essex) from 1999 to 2007, and in 2011 was restored and opened to the public at [[Harwich]].<ref>http://www.lv18.org</ref>\n*LV21; Light Vessel 21 was built in 1963 by Philip & Son and saw most of her service off the Kent Coast on the Varne and East Goodwin stations. The vessel is now in private ownership and has been transformed into a floating art centre and performance venue. Currently moored at St Andrew's Quay, Gravesend, Kent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lv21.co.uk/|title=LV21 \u2013 Art Culture Education Heritage Performance Venue}}</ref>\n*LV23; Light Vessel 23, now called the Mersey Planet, has been removed from Liverpool on 21 September 2016. Location Sharpness docks.\n*LV38; Light Vessel 38 was built of oak in 1860 and was retired in 1941. It was scrapped at [[Grays, Essex|Grays]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/139/light-vessel-38-gull|title=Name Light Vessel 38 Gull &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV44; Light Vessel 44 was built in 1869, sold in 1945, and now lies derelict at [[Pitsea]] Country Park.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/140/light-vessel-44-Carnaervon-bay</ref>\n*LV50; Light Vessel 50 was built in 1879 and originally stationed off the [[Isles of Scilly]]. It was decommissioned in the 1900s, and bought by the Royal Northumberland Yacht Club in 1952 for use as a clubhouse. It was still in use in 2013.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/141/light-vessel-50-h.y.-tyne</ref>\n*LV55; Light Vessel 55 was built (along with LV54 and LV59) by [[Charles Hill & Sons]] of Bristol in 1885. It was in service until springing a leak in 1953 and was towed to Barry Docks for repair. Later sold as a burnt-out wreck in 1954 to the Cabot Cruising Club in [[Bristol]], she is now called the ''John Sebastian'' and is located in Bathurst Basin, albeit with a considerably remodelled lantern.\n*LV67; Light Vessel 67 is now a wreck somewhere off the west coast of the British Isles.\n*LV72; Light Vessel 72 was built in 1903 by [[John Crown & Sons]] of Sunderland<ref>[http://www.sunderlandmaritimeheritage.org.uk/Shipyards/Crowns.html ''Ships Built at Crowns''], accessed 2014-04-20</ref> for Trinity House. LV72 was one of two Light Vessels which saw service on [[D Day]] carrying the name \"JUNO\" the ship marked a safe passage through a minefield for the landing craft en route to the invasion beaches. She was sold out of service in 1973 to Steel Supply Co., [[Neath]] for scrapping. When sold she was the oldest vessel in the Trinity House fleet. She was later considered for conversion to a floating night club but the project did not go ahead. After decades of neglect, she is now lying in poor condition, severely listing on a mud berth near the [[Swing Bridge, River Neath|River Neath's Swing Bridge]] and does not float.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV72/lv72gb.htm</ref>\n*LV78; spit Light Vessel 78 was built in 1914 by [[John I. Thornycroft & Company]] of Southampton. In 2010 she was moved to Southampton Docks for a planned restoration.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/144/light-vessel-78-Calshot</ref>\n*LV80; Light Vessel 80 was built at Liverpool in 1914. Sold in 1977 and last seen at Hoo near Rochester in 2004.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV80/lv80gb.htm</ref>\n*LV83; Light Vessel 83 sank in 1967 after a collision, and lies at the bottom of the North Sea off [[Easington, North Yorkshire|Easington]], Cleveland.\n*LV86; Light Vessel 86 was built in 1931 on the Isle of Wight, was sold in 1974 and is now used as a houseboat at [[Hoo St Werburgh|Hoo]] Marina in Kent.<ref>[http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/488/light-vessel-86-nore ''Light Vessel 86 Nore''], National Historic Ships Register, accessed 2014-04-20</ref>\n*LV87; Light Vessel 87 was built in 1932 in Glasgow. She was sold in 1973 and now belongs to the Haven Ports Yacht Club in Suffolk.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV87/LV87GB.HTM</ref>\n*LV88; Light Vessel 88  was built in 1936 by Philip & Son and began service at the Cockle station, was sold in 1977, and was last seen in [[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/645/light-vessel-88|title=Name Light Vessel 88 &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV89; Light Vessel 89 was built in 1936 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1974, became a pub in Bristol, and was broken up in 1995.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/lv89/lv89gb.htm</ref>\n*LV90; Light Vessel 90 was built in 1937 by Philip & Son. On 25 October 1940, the South Goodwin Lightship was bombed by the Germans and sunk. The replacement sank in a storm in 1954 at the South Goodwin station. The next replacement South Goodwin Lightvessel was decommissioned and was towed away on 26 July 2006.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/lv90/lv90gb.htm</ref>\n*LV91; Light Vessel 91 was built in 1937 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1977 and became a floating museum in Swansea.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV91/lv91gb.htm</ref>\n*LV93; Light Vessel 93 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was sold in 2004 and moved to the London Docklands. She is now in use as a photographic studio and location.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV93/lv93gb.htm</ref>\n*LV94; Light Vessel 94 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1990. In 2008 it was moored in [[Amsterdam]] and hired out for events.<ref>http://www.worldlighthouses.org/Lighthship/UK/LV94/lv94.htm</ref>\n*LV95; Light Vessel 95 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was sold in 2004. In 2011 she was being used as a recording studio at [[Trinity Buoy Wharf]] in London.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV95/lv95gb.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lighthouses]]\n*[[Trinity House]]\n*[[Men of the Lightship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Lightships of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Lightvessels}}\n\n[[Category:Lightships of the United Kingdom| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|lighthouses|List of lighthouses in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\nThe history of '''lightvessels in the United Kingdom''' goes back over 250 years. This page also gives a list of [[lightvessel]] stations within the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Channel Islands]] and [[Gibraltar]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe world's first lightvessel was the result of a business partnership between Robert Hamblin, an impoverished former [[barber]] and ship manager from [[King's Lynn]], and David Avery, a regular investor in small projects.<ref name=naish>Naish, J. M. ''Seamarks: Their History and Development'', Stanford Maritime, 1985, {{ISBN|978-0-540-07309-2}}, p. 107</ref> In 1730 the pair secured a government licence to moor a ship {{ndash}} with a prominent light affixed to it to serve as a navigation aid {{ndash}} at the [[Nore]] in the [[Thames]] mouth. Hamblin and Avery intended to profit from the vessel by collecting a fee from passing merchant vessels. The licence was opposed by [[Trinity House]] which considered that it possessed a monopoly on construction and maintenance of navigation aids in British waters. After extensive legal dispute the licence was revoked in 1732 and Trinity House assumed direct responsibility for the proposed lightship; Hamblin and Avery were granted nominal lease revenues in exchange.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Nautical Magazine and Naval Chronicle for 1865|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=624|year=2013|isbn=9781108054911}}</ref> The Nore lightship commenced operations in 1734.<ref name=Marcus>{{cite book|last=Marcus|first=G.J.|title=Heart of Oak: A Survey of British Sea Power in the Georgian Era|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1975|pages=[https://archive.org/details/heartofoaksurvey0000marc/page/53 53\u201354]|isbn=0192158120|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/heartofoaksurvey0000marc/page/53}}</ref>\n\nA further lightvessel was placed at the Dudgeon station, off the [[Norfolk]] coast, in 1736, with others following at [[Owers Bank]] (1788) and the [[Goodwin Sands]] (1793).<ref name=Marcus/> Many others were commissioned during the nineteenth century, especially off England's east coast and the approaches to the Thames, where there were many treacherous [[shoal]]s.\n\n[[File:Lv-Nore.jpg|thumb|right|Lightship LV86, on station at the Nore from 1931 to 1974]]\n\nFollowing their acquisition of the patent, all English and Welsh lightvessels were maintained by Trinity House, with the exception of the four vessels in the approaches to the [[River Mersey]], which were maintained by the [[Mersey Docks and Harbour Board]] until 1973, and those in the [[Humber Estuary]], which were the responsibility of the Humber Conservancy Board. In order to act as effective [[daymark]]s Trinity House lightvessels were painted red, with the station name in large white letters on the side of the hull, and a system of balls and cones at the masthead for identification. The first revolving light was fitted to the Swin Middle lightvessel in 1837: others used occulting or flashing lights. White lights were preferred for visibility though red and very occasionally green (as with the Mouse lightvessel) were also used.<ref name=miltoun>Miltoun, F. (ed) ''[http://www.kellscraft.com/ShipsandShipping/ShipsandShippingCh11.html Ships and Shipping]'', Moring Ltd, 1903, Ch. 11</ref>\n\n===Communications and safety===\n\nCommunication with lightvessels proved to be a major problem for Trinity House; lightvessel crews were well-placed to observe ships in distress, but could not always alert [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution|lifeboats]] on shore. After a series of shipwrecks, an experiment was conducted whereby a nine-mile undersea cable was run from the Sunk lightvessel in the [[Thames Estuary]] to the [[post office]] at [[Walton-on-the-Naze]]. This was intended to commence in 1884, but was plagued by delays;<ref name=hansard>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1884/may/16/board-of-trade-telegraphic-communication BOARD OF TRADE \u2014 TELEGRAPHIC COMMUNICATION WITH LIGHT VESSELS], [[Hansard]] 16-05-1884</ref> the trial was unsuccessful as the cable repeatedly broke. As a result of a motion brought forward by Sir [[Edward Birkbeck]], a [[Royal Commission]] was established to look at the issue of 'electrical communication' and gave its first Report in 1892;<ref name=hansard2>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1892/apr/26/coast-communications COAST COMMUNICATIONS], [[Hansard]] 26-04-1892</ref><ref name=hansard1>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1893/mar/21/communication-with-lighthouses COMMUNICATION WITH LIGHTHOUSES], [[Hansard]] 21-03-1893</ref> the East Goodwin lightvessel was used during one of [[Guglielmo Marconi]]'s early experiments in radio transmission in 1896.<ref name=marconi>{{cite book|last=Baker|first= W. J.|title=History of the Marconi Company|publisher= Routledge|year= 1998| ISBN= 978-0-415-14624-1|pages=39\u201340}}</ref> The world's first radio distress signal was transmitted by the East Goodwin lightvessel's radio operator on 17 March 1899, after the [[merchant vessel]] ''Elbe'' ran aground on the [[Goodwin Sands|Goodwins]], while on 30 April that year, the East Goodwin vessel transmitted a distress signal on its own behalf, when the [[SS]] ''R. F. Matthews'' rammed it in a dense fog. Safety was further improved by the development of more powerful lamps and through the replacement by [[foghorn]]s of the [[gong]]s previously used as fog signals.\n\n===Crew===\n\nUntil the later 20th century, all Trinity House vessels were permanently manned. An 1861 article in the [[Cornhill Magazine]] described lightshipmen as being paid 55 shillings a month (in addition to drawing 1 shilling and sixpence a week \"in lieu of 3 gallons of [[small beer|small-beer]]\"): the vessels were supplied, and the crews relieved, once a month. It was also noted that \"a general tone of decent, orderly and superior conduct\" was observed, that the men were \"very respectable [...] swearing and profane language are [...] prohibited\" and that every man was supplied with a Bible as well as \"a library of varied and entertaining literature\".<ref name=cornhill>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dbkCAAAAIAAJ Light-Vessels]'', The Cornhill Magazine, III (1861), 39.</ref>\n\nBy the start of the 20th century, Trinity House lightvessels had a crew of 11, of whom seven (a master and six ratings) would be on active duty at any one time. It was an extremely demanding and dangerous profession, and it would take 15 to 20 years of service to be promoted to master.<ref name=portcities1>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConNarrative.64/chapterId/1506/Trinity-House.html Trinity House], portcities.org, accessed 02-09-08</ref>\n\n===Replacement===\n\nThe majority of British lightvessels were decommissioned during the 1970s - 1980s and replaced with light floats or [[Lanby buoy|LANBY]] buoys, which were vastly cheaper to maintain: in 1974 at the time of Trinity House's original development project, lightship annual running costs at \u00a330,000 were ten times those of the LANBY.<ref name=design1974>Rowlands, D. [http://vads.ac.uk/diad/article.php?title=310&year=1974&article=d.310.39 \"Points of Reference\"], ''Design'' 310 (1974)</ref>\n\nThe remaining UK lightvessels have now been converted to unmanned operation and most now use [[solar power]].\n\n==Lightvessel stations==\n\nThe following are lightvessel ''stations''; i.e. a named position at which a lightvessel was placed, rather than the names of vessels themselves. Individual vessels were often transferred between different stations during their existence but they kept their Trinity House LV number. Stations themselves were occasionally changed, especially during wartime, when lights were only displayed in response to specific shipping needs. It is likely that photographs on various websites showing named lightvessels, may appear to be structurally different to comparable records on other web pages due to the fact that the particular LV might have been withdrawn from a station after photographing and being towed away for drydocking, overhaul and possible direction to a new station and therefore a different lightvessel would have been substituted at the named station on withdrawal of the previous LV. This has been most evident on those LVs that have been withdrawn and shipped to another port at home or abroad to become a floating museum, floating restaurant, 'clubhouse', etc. Scarweather LV and Helwick LV have for instance changed their r\u00f4le in their lifetime and their appearance on various records varies considerably.\n\n===England===\n\n====Active lightvessel stations====\n\nThe following are active stations at which Trinity House still maintains unmanned lightships, which also act as [[weather station]]s.\n\n[[File:Lightvessel East Goodwin.jpg|thumb|right|The East Goodwin lightvessel while under repair at [[Harwich]]]]\n\n*[[Channel Light Vessel Automatic|Channel Lightvessel]]  (north of [[Guernsey]])\n*F3 Lightvessel (middle of [[English Channel]], east of [[Ramsgate]])\n*East Goodwin Lightvessel ([[Goodwin Sands]])\n*[[Greenwich Light Vessel Automatic|Greenwich Lightvessel]]  (south of [[East Sussex]] on the [[Prime Meridian]])\n*[[Sandettie Light Vessel Automatic|Sandettie Lightvessel]]  (north of [[Calais]])\n*[[Sevenstones Lightship|Sevenstones Lightvessel]]  (west of [[Land's End]])\n*Sunk Lightvessel ([[Thames Estuary]])\n*[[Varne Bank|Varne Lightvessel]]  (southwest of [[Dover]])\n\n====Former lightvessel stations====\n[[File:Calshot Spit Lightship.jpg|thumb|Lightship LV78, formerly at [[Calshot Spit]] station]]\n\n*Bar ([[Mersey Estuary]]; maintained by MDHB)\n*Barrow Deep (Barrow Deep channel, Thames Estuary)\n*[[Black Deep]] (Thames Estuary)\n*Brake (Brake Sand, near [[Goodwin Sands]])\n*Bull (Bull Sands, mouth of the [[Humber Estuary]]; maintained by Humber Conservancy Board)\n*[[Calshot Spit]]\n*Cockle (North Sea)\n*Cork (Cork Bank, off [[Harwich]])\n*Corton (North Sea)\n*Crosby (Mersey Estuary; maintained by MDHB)\n*Docking Shoal, Norfolk coast\n*Inner / Outer Dowsing (North Sea; Inner Dowsing was the last manned lightship station, replaced by the Dowsing lighthouse in 1991)<ref name=dowsing>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConNarrative.64/chapterId/1506/Trinity-House.html Trinity House], portcities.org</ref>\n*Dudgeon (North Sea; the Dudgeon lightvessel was bombed by the [[Luftwaffe]] on 29 January 1940. Only one crew member, John Sanders, survived. The incident was the subject of a 1940 British Government [[propaganda]] film, ''[[Men of the Lightship]]''.<ref>{{Cite video  | people = David MacDonald (Director); Alberto Cavalcanti (Producer)  | title = Men of the Lightship    | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0309856/  | medium = Film (35mm, 24 mins, black & white)  | publisher = [[GPO Film Unit]]  | date = 1940}}</ref>\n*Edinburgh (Thames Estuary; the name refers to the Edinburgh Channel)\n*English and Welsh Grounds [[Bristol Channel]] (now a clubhouse in Bathurst Basin, Bristol)\n*Falls (Dover Strait)\n*Formby (Mersey Estuary, maintained by MDHB)\n*Galloper (Galloper shoal, North Sea)\n*Girdler (Thames Estuary)\n*Gull (marked the Gull Stream on the Goodwin Sands)- was rammed and sunk on 18 March 1929 by the City of York, resulting in the death of Captain Williams of the lightship. In 1947 it was bought for \u00a3750 by Thurrock Yacht Club, and towed to Grays to become the club\u2019s headquarters. It was last used as a clubhouse in 1971.The Gull was then abandoned and now suffers from regular acts of vandalism and degradation through river action.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thurrock Gazette|title=Landmark mast of Gull lightship is removed|url=http://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/4361437.Landmark_mast_of_Gull_lightship_is_removed/|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref> \n*Gunfleet (Gunfleet Sands, Thames Estuary; replaced by [[Gunfleet Lighthouse]] in 1850)\n*Hasborough (North Sea)\n*Humber (maintained by Humber Conservancy Board)\n*[[Kentish Knock (England)|Kentish Knock]]\n*Knoll (Smith's Knoll, North Sea) off Norfolk\n*Leman and Ower (North Sea)\n*Longsand (Thames Estuary)\n*[[Morecambe Bay]]\n*Mouse (Mouse Sand, Thames Estuary)\n*Nab ([[Straits of Dover]]; replaced by the [[Nab Tower]] in 1920)\n*Newarp (North Sea)\n*[[Nore]] (Thames Estuary; the world's first manned lightship, 1731)\n*North [[Goodwin Sands|Goodwin]]\n*Northwestern (Mersey Estuary, maintained by MDHB)\n*Outer Gabbard (North Sea)\n*Owers ([[Owers Bank]], off [[Selsey Bill]]). Replaced with a beacon. (LV Owers now a wreck in [[Tel Aviv]] harbour)\n*Royal Sovereign (off [[Eastbourne]]; replaced with [[Royal Sovereign lighthouse]] 1971)\n*Shambles (the Shambles Bank, off [[Portland Bill]])\n*Shipwash (North Sea, off [[Harwich]])\n*South Goodwin lightvessel replaced the land based South Foreland Low lighthouse, also known as Old St Margaret's Lighthouse. On 25 October 1940, the South Goodwin Lightship was bombed by the Germans and sunk. The replacement lightvessel, LV90 sank on 27 November 1954 when cables to her two sea anchors broke in a hurricane-force storm, the worst storm in two centuries. The ship ran onto the Goodwin Sands close to the Keller Gut and turned on her side. The seven crew members perished, the only survivor being Ronald Murton an ornithologist from the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries. The wreck of the ship can still be seen at low tide. The next replacement ship was decommissioned and was towed away on 26 July 2006.<ref name=goodwin>[http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/conMediaFile.123/Crew-of-the-South-Goodwin-light-vessel.html South Goodwin Light Vessel], portcities.org</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trinityhousehistory.wordpress.com/tag/south-goodwin-lightvessel/|title=South Goodwin Lightvessel {{!}} Trinity House History|website=trinityhousehistory.wordpress.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1070066|desc=ST MARGARET'S OLD LIGHTHOUSE, St. Margaret's At Cliffe |accessdate=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n*Spurn ([[Spurn Head]]). Maintained by Humber Conservancy Board. A former [[Spurn Lightship|Spurn lightvessel]] is preserved at [[Hull Marina]].\n[[File:SFEC HULL .SPURN1.JPG|thumb|right|Preserved former Humber Conservancy Board ''Spurn'' lightvessel]]\n*Swin Middle (Swin Channel, Thames Estuary)\n*Tongue (Tongue Sands, Thames Estuary)\n*Lynn Well (entrance to [[The Wash]]); replaced with a [[Lanby buoy|LANBY]] (Large Automatic Navigation BuoY) September 1973\n*Would (North Sea)\n\n===Scotland, Isle of Man===\n\nLightvessels in Scotland and the Isle of Man were maintained by the [[Northern Lighthouse Board]], with the exception of one maintained by the Clyde Lighthouse Trust. Only the ''North Carr'' station was manned.\n\n*[[Bahama Bank]] (off [[Maughold Head]], [[Isle of Man]]; replaced by Maughold Head lighthouse 1914)\n*North Carr, [[Dundee]]\n*Otter Rock (south-west of the [[Isle of Mull]]).  Scottish Maritime Museum in Irving has a small scale coloured General Arrangement (1923) from Builder (Clyde Shipbuilding and Engineering Co. Ltd. hull #249, 60&nbsp;ft [183 m]).\n*Skeirinoe (Sgeir In-ao, near Scalpay, Harris)<ref>{{cite map|publisher  = [[Ordnance Survey]]|title = Map of Skeirinoe lightvessel (via National Library of Scotland maps API|url = http://nls.tileserver.com/?lat=57.84&lng=-6.55&zoom=13|edition = Popular Edition (Scotland)|year = 1920\u20131930|scale  = 1:253\u2009440|accessdate = 2011-08-13}}</ref>\n\n===Wales===\n\n[[File:Bateau feu Scarweather.jpg|thumb|Scarweather]]\nFormer Welsh lightships were maintained by Trinity House. Remaining substitute navigational aids still are.\n\n*Breaksea (off Barry (Breaksea Spit), Bristol Channel) Replaced by a LANBY, then a lightfloat and currently a lighted buoy with [[Radar beacon (racon)|RACON]] radar facility\n*Helwick (off [[Worms Head]])\n*[[Milford Haven (harbour)|Milford Haven Lightvessel]]\n*Scarweather ([[Swansea Bay]]; replaced with buoy 1989)\n*St Gowan (off Pembrokeshire coast). The station once carried the name St Govan, i.e., spelling change\n\n===Northern Ireland===\n*Petrel Lightvessel\n*South Rock Lightvessel\n\n==Decommissioned lightvessels==\nThe central records of the UK's light vessels were lost when Trinity House was bombed in 1940.\n\n*LV1; Light Vessel 1 was built in 1946 by [[Philip and Son|Philip & Son Ltd.]], [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]], England. In 1993 she was decommissioned and sold to Dean & Reddyhoff Ltd., [[Southampton]], for use as marina club house at Gosport, [[Hampshire]].<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV01/lv01gb.htm</ref>\n*LV3; Light Vessel 3 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. It sank off the coast of [[Israel]] in 2000.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160327090123/http://broadcasting-fleet.com/kingdavid2.htm</ref>\n*LV4; Light Vessel 4 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1989. In 1991 was sold to the Mus\u00e9e de Bateau in Douarnenez, [[France]], for \u00a340,000. She has been restored and renamed \"Scarweather\".<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV04/lv4gb.htm</ref>\n*LV5; Light Vessel 5 was built in 1947 by Philip & Son. She was deployed as relief lightship to replace vessels undergoing refit or otherwise out of commission.  She served, among other stations, the South Goodwin in 1961, the Tongue in 1973, the Falls from 1973 to 1976 and the Varne in 1977.  Her last station was the South Goodwin again, before being withdrawn from service for conversion to unmanned operation.<ref>From text explaining the LV5's catoptric light system in the Maritime museum, Ramsgate, England.</ref>\n*LV8; Light Vessel 8 was built in 1949 by Philip & Son and decommissioned in 1991. In 2005 Radio Waddenzee bought the lightship and towed it from Rotterdam to Harlingen, [[Netherlands]], where she is used as a radio station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101022823/http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV08/lv08gb.htm|title=Trinity House lightvessel no. 8 - LV 8 - Radio Waddenzee - Jenni Baynton|date=1 January 2014|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n*LV11; [[Lightvessel No. 11|Light Vessel 11]] was built in 1951 by Philip & Son and decommissioned in 1988. She was saved from scrap and towed to the repair yard in the Waalhaven in Rotterdam, [[Netherlands]]. Rebuilt into a maritime restaurant.\n*LV12; [[Spurn Lightship|Light Vessel 12]] was constructed in 1927 by Goole Shipbuilding and Repairing Company Ltd., and decommissioned in 1975. After being acquired by the Hull City Council, since 1987, she has become a museum vessel in Hull Marina.\n*LV13; Light Vessel 13 was built in 1952 Philip & Son and transferred to Hamburg in 1991, where she was used as a restaurant and hotel.\n*LV14; [[Lightship 2000|Light Vessel 14]] was built in 1953 by Philip & Son, decommissioned in 1991, and opened in 2000 in [[Cardiff]] as a church ship. Works No.1246, it was removed from Cardiff docks on financial grounds on 18 May 2015 and towed to Sharpness for drydocking and refurbishment. The press had stated that it was to become a floating museum at Newnham in Gloucestershire and was reported as being seen there in August 2016. \n*LV15; Light Vessel 15 was built in 1954 by Philip & Son, sold in 1988 and is now used by a church charity Fellowship afloat near the river Blackwater in Essex.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV15/lv15gb.htm</ref>\n*LV16; Light Vessel 16 was built in 1954 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1988 and currently serves as the [[Sea Cadet Corps (United Kingdom)|Sea Cadets]] training ship TS Colne Light moored at the Hythe Quay in [[Colchester]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/1573/colne-light|title=Name Colne Light &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV18; Light Vessel 18 was built in 1958 by Philip & Son, sold in 1997, was used by pirate radio nostalgia stations (RSLs & BBC Essex) from 1999 to 2007, and in 2011 was restored and opened to the public at [[Harwich]].<ref>http://www.lv18.org</ref>\n*LV21; Light Vessel 21 was built in 1963 by Philip & Son and saw most of her service off the Kent Coast on the Varne and East Goodwin stations. The vessel is now in private ownership and has been transformed into a floating art centre and performance venue. Currently moored at St Andrew's Quay, Gravesend, Kent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lv21.co.uk/|title=LV21 \u2013 Art Culture Education Heritage Performance Venue}}</ref>\n*LV23; Light Vessel 23, now called the Mersey Planet, has been removed from Liverpool on 21 September 2016. Location Sharpness docks.\n*LV38; Light Vessel 38 was built of oak in 1860 and was retired in 1941. It was scrapped at [[Grays]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/139/light-vessel-38-gull|title=Name Light Vessel 38 Gull &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV44; Light Vessel 44 was built in 1869, sold in 1945, and now lies derelict at [[Pitsea]] Country Park.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/140/light-vessel-44-Carnaervon-bay</ref>\n*LV50; Light Vessel 50 was built in 1879 and originally stationed off the [[Isles of Scilly]]. It was decommissioned in the 1900s, and bought by the Royal Northumberland Yacht Club in 1952 for use as a clubhouse. It was still in use in 2013.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/141/light-vessel-50-h.y.-tyne</ref>\n*LV55; Light Vessel 55 was built (along with LV54 and LV59) by [[Charles Hill & Sons]] of Bristol in 1885. It was in service until springing a leak in 1953 and was towed to Barry Docks for repair. Later sold as a burnt-out wreck in 1954 to the Cabot Cruising Club in [[Bristol]], she is now called the ''John Sebastian'' and is located in Bathurst Basin, albeit with a considerably remodelled lantern.\n*LV67; Light Vessel 67 is now a wreck somewhere off the west coast of the British Isles.\n*LV72; Light Vessel 72 was built in 1903 by [[John Crown & Sons]] of Sunderland<ref>[http://www.sunderlandmaritimeheritage.org.uk/Shipyards/Crowns.html ''Ships Built at Crowns''], accessed 2014-04-20</ref> for Trinity House. LV72 was one of two Light Vessels which saw service on [[D Day]] carrying the name \"JUNO\" the ship marked a safe passage through a minefield for the landing craft en route to the invasion beaches. She was sold out of service in 1973 to Steel Supply Co., [[Neath]] for scrapping. When sold she was the oldest vessel in the Trinity House fleet. She was later considered for conversion to a floating night club but the project did not go ahead. After decades of neglect, she is now lying in poor condition, severely listing on a mud berth near the [[Swing Bridge, River Neath|River Neath's Swing Bridge]] and does not float.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV72/lv72gb.htm</ref>\n*LV78; spit Light Vessel 78 was built in 1914 by [[John I. Thornycroft & Company]] of Southampton. In 2010 she was moved to Southampton Docks for a planned restoration.<ref>http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/144/light-vessel-78-Calshot</ref>\n*LV80; Light Vessel 80 was built at Liverpool in 1914. Sold in 1977 and last seen at Hoo near Rochester in 2004.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV80/lv80gb.htm</ref>\n*LV83; Light Vessel 83 sank in 1967 after a collision, and lies at the bottom of the North Sea off [[Easington, North Yorkshire|Easington]], Cleveland.\n*LV86; Light Vessel 86 was built in 1931 on the Isle of Wight, was sold in 1974 and is now used as a houseboat at [[Hoo St Werburgh|Hoo]] Marina in Kent.<ref>[http://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/488/light-vessel-86-nore ''Light Vessel 86 Nore''], National Historic Ships Register, accessed 2014-04-20</ref>\n*LV87; Light Vessel 87 was built in 1932 in Glasgow. She was sold in 1973 and now belongs to the Haven Ports Yacht Club in Suffolk.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV87/LV87GB.HTM</ref>\n*LV88; Light Vessel 88  was built in 1936 by Philip & Son and began service at the Cockle station, was sold in 1977, and was last seen in [[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/645/light-vessel-88|title=Name Light Vessel 88 &#124; National Historic Ships|website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk}}</ref>\n*LV89; Light Vessel 89 was built in 1936 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1974, became a pub in Bristol, and was broken up in 1995.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/lv89/lv89gb.htm</ref>\n*LV90; Light Vessel 90 was built in 1937 by Philip & Son. On 25 October 1940, the South Goodwin Lightship was bombed by the Germans and sunk. The replacement sank in a storm in 1954 at the South Goodwin station. The next replacement South Goodwin Lightvessel was decommissioned and was towed away on 26 July 2006.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/lv90/lv90gb.htm</ref>\n*LV91; Light Vessel 91 was built in 1937 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1977 and became a floating museum in Swansea.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV91/lv91gb.htm</ref>\n*LV93; Light Vessel 93 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was sold in 2004 and moved to the London Docklands. She is now in use as a photographic studio and location.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV93/lv93gb.htm</ref>\n*LV94; Light Vessel 94 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was decommissioned in 1990. In 2008 it was moored in [[Amsterdam]] and hired out for events.<ref>http://www.worldlighthouses.org/Lighthship/UK/LV94/lv94.htm</ref>\n*LV95; Light Vessel 95 was built in 1939 by Philip & Son. She was sold in 2004. In 2011 she was being used as a recording studio at [[Trinity Buoy Wharf]] in London.<ref>http://www.feuerschiffseite.de/SCHIFFE/ENGLAND/LV95/lv95gb.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lighthouses]]\n*[[Trinity House]]\n*[[Men of the Lightship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Lightships of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Lightvessels}}\n\n[[Category:Lightships of the United Kingdom| ]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lightvessels_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Elzie Odom", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|image           = Elzie Odom (10018979).jpg\n|name            = Elzie Odom \n|caption         =\n|order           = 24th Mayor of [[Arlington, Texas]]\n|term_start      = May 6, 1997\n|term_end        = May 3, 2003\n|predecessor     = Richard Greene\n|successor       = [[Robert Cluck]]\n|birth_name      = Elzie Delano Odom\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1929|5|10}}\n|birth_place     = [[Shankleville, Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place     =\n|party           = \n|spouse          = Ruby Lee Truvillion\n|profession      = \n}}\n\n'''Elzie Odom''' is an American politician, community activist, and former postal worker who served as mayor of [[Arlington, Texas]], from 1997 to 2003 and as an Arlington city councilman from 1990 to 1997. He was born in [[Newton County, Texas]], in 1929, and raised in the [[Freedmen's town|freedom colony]] of [[Shankleville, Texas]]. He attended [[Prairie View A&M University|Prairie View College]] before becoming a letter carrier with the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) in 1950 in [[Orange, Texas]]. He also became the first African American elected as a city official when he served on the [[West Orange-Cove Consolidated Independent School District|Orange school district]] board starting in May 1965. \n\nOdom became one of the first African American postal inspectors in the country in 1967, the same year he was transferred to [[Los Angeles]]. He was transferred to [[San Antonio]] by the USPS in 1970 and finally to Arlington in 1979. He retired from the USPS in 1987. \n\nOdom first ran for city council in Arlington in 1989 and was first elected in 1990. During his tenure, he made the city's boards and commissions more diverse and representative of the city's population. As president of the Arlington Sport Facilities Development Authority, he oversaw construction of [[The Ballpark In Arlington|The Ballpark in Arlington]] and together with the rest of the city council successfully kept [[General Motors]]' [[Arlington Assembly]] and the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in Arlington. \n\nIn 1997, Odom ran for mayor, winning 50.19% of votes as [[Voter turnout|turnout]] reached a 10-year high. His major accomplishments as mayor included advocating for Arlington youth, supporting programs for citizens with disabilities and seniors, paying off The Ballpark in Arlington ahead of schedule, and creating a street maintenance sales program. He retired from office in 2003. \n\n== Early life and career ==\nElzie Odom was born on May 10, 1929, in [[Newton County, Texas]]. He was raised in the [[Freedmen's town|freedom colony]] of [[Shankleville, Texas]], which was established by his ancestors, James (\"Jim\") and Winnie Shankle. The Odom family were [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence farmers]], raising cows, chickens, and pigs and growing crops for food. Odom's father worked as a [[Carpentry|carpenter]] and community [[Funeral director|undertaker]], and his mother maintained a small [[general store]] across the street from their family home. Both parents later served in various positions at their local church, Mount Hope Baptist Church. Odom was the second youngest of eight siblings.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Odom|first=Elzie D.|title=Counting My Blessings: A Memoir|publisher=Bloomington, IN : Authorhouse|year=2011|isbn=9781468500813|location=|pages=}}</ref>  \n\nOdom met his wife, Ruby Truvillion, while he was a junior in high school. Ruby is the daughter of Reverend Henry Truvillion and O'Neal Bluitt. After graduating from [[Burkeville, Texas|Burkeville Colored High School]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Odom Relies on Cooperative coalition-Building Politics|last=|first=|date=April 20, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Odom attended [[Prairie View A&M University|Prairie View College]] for one year before leaving school to be a carpentry apprentice under his father. Elzie and Ruby were married in July 1947. They have two children, Elzie Odom, Jr,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmupumc.org/NewPage712445712445|title=Rev. Elzie D. Odom, Jr., Senior Pastor|last=Pleasant Mound United Methodist Church|first=|date=|website=Pleasant Mound United Methodist Church|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref> and Dr. Barbara Odom-Wesley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/city_hall/government/city_council/members/council_member_district_8|title=COUNCIL MEMBER DR. BARBARA ODOM-WESLEY DISTRICT 8|last=Arlington City Hall|first=|date=|website=Arlington Texas Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 1950, the family moved to [[Orange, Texas]], in pursuit of greater employment opportunities. In 1950, Odom became a letter carrier with the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) in Orange,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=City of Arlington Elects First Black Mayor|last=|first=|date=May 1997|work=The Black Economic Times, Fort Worth/Arlington|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and earned supplemental income through sales jobs. Ruby was hired to work at the office of a local black dentist, and became a [[Radiographer|Registered Radiologic Technologist]]. The Odoms were active in their community, helping to establish a kindergarten and preschool for black children and participating in the local [[Parent\u2013teacher association|parent-teacher association]]. The Odoms were active members of the [[NAACP]], and in 1956-1957 they attended and held secret meetings in response to state persecution of the NAACP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crmvet.org/tim/timhis56.htm#1956naacp|title=Civil Rights Movement History: 1956|last=|first=|date=|website=Civil Rights Movement Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref>  \n\nOdom was elected to serve on the [[West Orange-Cove Consolidated Independent School District|Orange school district]] board in May 1965, making him the first African American to be elected as a city official in [[Orange County, Texas|Orange County]].<ref name=\":4\" />  \n\nIn 1967, Odom became a postal inspector and was transferred to [[Los Angeles]], where the family stayed for three years. He was one of the earliest black postal inspectors in the nation. After three years in Los Angeles, the family transferred to [[San Antonio]] before a final transfer to the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas region]] in 1979, where the family settled in Arlington.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Crawford|first=Selwyn|url=|title=Elzie Odom: Leaving a Positive Legacy for Future Generations|date=February 27, 2000|work=The Dallas Morning News: High Profile|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Odom retired from the USPS in 1987.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Arlington City Council ===\nIn 1989, Odom ran for [[city council]] in Arlington against incumbent Theron Brooks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Black History Month|date=February 16, 1993|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Afterwards, he was appointed to the [[Planning and zoning commission|Planning and Zoning Commission]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He ran again for city council the next election cycle and won the [[run-off election]] for Place 4 on May 19, 1990. He was the first African American to be elected to the Arlington City Council.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/news/my_arlington_t_x/news_archive/2017_archived_news/may_2017/20_year_elzie_odom_reflects_on_his_arlington_dream|title=20 YEARS AFTER BEING ELECTED, FORMER MAYOR ELZIE ODOM REFLECTS ON HIS ARLINGTON DREAM|last=Office of Communication|first=|date=May 18, 2017|website=Arlington|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> While he was a member of the city council, he worked on transportation, mobility, and redistricting issues facing Arlington.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/residents/about_arlington/history_of_arlington/hall_of_mayors/elzie_odom|title=ELZIE ODOM|last=City of Arlington|first=|date=|website=Arlington|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Odom and the city council increased minority representation on Arlington's boards and commissions, mirroring the city's population. In 1990, only two members of city boards and commissions were [[Person of color|people of color]]. By 1996, 22% of members of Arlington's boards and commissions were people of color.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Garcia|first=Eric|url=|title=City panels reflect minority numbers - Report shows that council's appointees are about proportionate to city's population - members say they want to increase minority representation|date=April 24, 1996|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> While in office, he served as president of the Arlington Sport Facilities Development Authority, oversaw construction of [[The Ballpark In Arlington|The Ballpark in Arlington]], and chaired the Arlington City Council's Youth Activities, Waste Water Treatment, Garbage Disposal, Community Development, and Employee Benefits committees. He also represented the city of Arlington on the [[North Central Texas Council of Governments]], the Tarrant County Housing Partnership, the Texas Municipal League, the Working Connection, and the State Attorney General's Municipal Advisory Committee.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Cole|first=Earnestine|url=|title=Council Member Odom Runs for Mayor of Arlington|date=March 26, 1997|work=La Vida News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> During his tenure, the council successfully kept [[General Motors]]' [[Arlington Assembly]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Worcester|first=Lea|title=Legendary Locals of Arlington, Texas|last2=Barker|first2=Evelyn|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-1-4671-0058-8|location=|pages=29}}</ref> and the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in Arlington.<ref name=\":3\" />   \n\n=== Mayor of Arlington ===\nIncumbent mayor [https://www.arlingtontx.gov/residents/about_arlington/history_of_arlington/hall_of_mayors/richard_greene Richard Greene] had served in office for a decade when he announced that he would not be seeking reelection in 1997. Odom did not immediately seek to run for office as Mayor of Arlington as he did not want to risk losing his District 1 single-member council seat,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Accessible and Approachable|last=Doclar|first=Mary|date=May 11, 1997|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram, The Weekly Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and it was not until he was inspired by a sermon at his church that he decided to run for mayor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Mayor-Elect Reflects on Historic Victory: Odom sees God as Key to Triumph|date=May 5, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 1997, Odom announced his plans to run for office. He stated that his reason for running was: \"because I care for my family, my city, and its people, I am running for Mayor of the greatest city in the world. I plan to run a clean and positive neighbor-to-neighbor campaign with a simple theme: Getting Results For Arlington.\" Odom outlined a 10-point plan for his future administration, which included improving traffic and mobility, reducing crime, encouraging public-private partnerships, addressing unnecessary spending, and economic development.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Council member Odom Runs for Mayor of Arlington|last=|first=|date=March 26, 1997|work=La Vida News: The Black Voice|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He received endorsements from council members and Arlington businesses.<ref name=\":2\" /> Odom won the election with 8,752 votes. His closest challenger was Laura Hightower, who won 7,060 votes.<ref name=\":0\" /> He and Hightower received 50.19% and 40.49% of the votes, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=It's Odom's Character, Supporters Say|last=Lee|first=Renee C.|date=May 11, 1997|work=Arlington Star-Telegram|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> City officials had estimated a voter turnout rate of 7.4%, but it reached 10%,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=10-percent Turnout Highest in a Decade|last=|first=|date=May 4, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> the highest in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rankin|first=Jennifer|url=|title=Turnout breaks 10-year high, officials say|date=May 4, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhile in office, Odom advocated for Arlington youth, inviting students to visit his office during winter break. He also supported programs for citizens with disabilities and seniors. During this time, Arlington taxpayers paid off The Ballpark in Arlington years ahead of the payment cutoff date, and the city created a street maintenance sales program. He retired in 2003.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2001 Arlington mayoral election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odom, Elzie}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Arlington, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas city council members]]\n[[Category:School board members in Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Newton County, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Orange, Texas]]\n[[Category:Prairie View A&M University alumni]]\n[[Category:NAACP activists]]\n[[Category:United States Postal Service people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|image           = Elzie Odom (10018979).jpg\n|name            = Elzie Odom \n|caption         =\n|order           = 24th Mayor of [[Arlington, Texas]]\n|term_start      = May 6, 1997\n|term_end        = May 3, 2003\n|predecessor     = Richard Greene\n|successor       = [[Robert Cluck]]\n|birth_name      = Elzie Delano Odom\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1929|5|10}}\n|birth_place     = [[Shankleville, Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place     =\n|party           = \n|spouse          = Ruby Lee Truvillion\n|profession      = \n}}\n\n'''Elzie Odom''' is an American politician, community activist, and former postal worker who served as mayor of [[Arlington, Texas]], from 1997 to 2003 and as an Arlington city councilman from 1990 to 1997. He was born in [[Newton County, Texas]], in 1929, and raised in the [[Freedmen's town|freedom colony]] of [[Shankleville, Texas]]. He attended [[Prairie View A&M University|Prairie View College]] before becoming a letter carrier with the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) in 1950 in [[Orange, Texas]]. He also became the first African American elected as a city official when he served on the [[West Orange-Cove Consolidated Independent School District|Orange school district]] board starting in May 1965. \n\nOdom became one of the first African American postal inspectors in the country in 1967, the same year he was transferred to [[Los Angeles]]. He was transferred to [[San Antonio]] by the USPS in 1970 and finally to Arlington in 1979. He retired from the USPS in 1987. \n\nOdom first ran for city council in Arlington in 1989 and was first elected in 1990. During his tenure, he made the city's boards and commissions more diverse and representative of the city's population. As president of the Arlington Sport Facilities Development Authority, he oversaw construction of [[The Ballpark In Arlington|The Ballpark in Arlington]] and together with the rest of the city council successfully kept [[General Motors]]' [[Arlington Assembly]] and the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in Arlington. \n\nIn 1997, Odom ran for mayor, winning 50.19% of votes as [[Voter turnout|turnout]] reached a 10-year high. His major accomplishments as mayor included advocating for Arlington youth, supporting programs for citizens with disabilities and seniors, paying off The Ballpark in Arlington ahead of schedule, and creating a street maintenance sales program. He retired from office in 2003. \n\n== Early life and career ==\nElzie Odom was born on May 10, 1929, in [[Newton County, Texas]]. He was raised in the [[Freedmen's town|freedom colony]] of [[Shankleville, Texas]], which was established by his ancestors, James (\"Jim\") and Winnie Shankle. The Odom family were [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence farmers]], raising cows, chickens, and pigs and growing crops for food. Odom's father worked as a [[Carpentry|carpenter]] and community [[Funeral director|undertaker]], and his mother maintained a small [[general store]] across the street from their family home. Both parents later served in various positions at their local church, Mount Hope Baptist Church. Odom was the second youngest of eight siblings.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Odom|first=Elzie D.|title=Counting My Blessings: A Memoir|publisher=Bloomington, IN : Authorhouse|year=2011|isbn=9781468500813|location=|pages=}}</ref>  \n\nOdom met his wife, Ruby Truvillion, while he was a junior in high school. Ruby is the daughter of Reverend Henry Truvillion and O'Neal Bluitt. After graduating from [[Burkeville, Texas|Burkeville Colored High School]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Odom Relies on Cooperative coalition-Building Politics|last=|first=|date=April 20, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Odom attended [[Prairie View A&M University|Prairie View College]] for one year before leaving school to be a carpentry apprentice under his father. Elzie and Ruby were married in July 1947. They have two children, Elzie Odom, Jr,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmupumc.org/NewPage712445712445|title=Rev. Elzie D. Odom, Jr., Senior Pastor|last=Pleasant Mound United Methodist Church|first=|date=|website=Pleasant Mound United Methodist Church|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref> and Dr. Barbara Odom-Wesley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/city_hall/government/city_council/members/council_member_district_8|title=COUNCIL MEMBER DR. BARBARA ODOM-WESLEY DISTRICT 8|last=Arlington City Hall|first=|date=|website=Arlington Texas Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 1950, the family moved to [[Orange, Texas]], in pursuit of greater employment opportunities. In 1950, Odom became a letter carrier with the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) in Orange,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=City of Arlington Elects First Black Mayor|last=|first=|date=May 1997|work=The Black Economic Times, Fort Worth/Arlington|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and earned supplemental income through sales jobs. Ruby was hired to work at the office of a local black dentist, and became a [[Radiographer|Registered Radiologic Technologist]]. The Odoms were active in their community, helping to establish a kindergarten and preschool for black children and participating in the local [[Parent\u2013teacher association|parent-teacher association]]. The Odoms were active members of the [[NAACP]], and in 1956-1957 they attended and held secret meetings in response to state persecution of the NAACP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crmvet.org/tim/timhis56.htm#1956naacp|title=Civil Rights Movement History: 1956|last=|first=|date=|website=Civil Rights Movement Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 Oct 2019}}</ref>  \n\nOdom was elected to serve on the [[West Orange-Cove Consolidated Independent School District|Orange school district]] board in May 1965, making him the first African American to be elected as a city official in [[Orange County, Texas|Orange County]].<ref name=\":4\" />  \n\nIn 1967, Odom became a postal inspector and was transferred to [[Los Angeles]], where the family stayed for three years. He was one of the earliest black postal inspectors in the nation. After three years in Los Angeles, the family transferred to [[San Antonio]] before a final transfer to the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas region]] in 1979, where the family settled in Arlington.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Crawford|first=Selwyn|url=|title=Elzie Odom: Leaving a Positive Legacy for Future Generations|date=February 27, 2000|work=The Dallas Morning News: High Profile|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Odom retired from the USPS in 1987.<ref name=\":1\" />  \n\n== Arlington City Council ==\nIn 1989, Odom ran for [[city council]] in Arlington against incumbent Theron Brooks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Black History Month|date=February 16, 1993|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Afterwards, he was appointed to the [[Planning and zoning commission|Planning and Zoning Commission]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He ran again for city council the next election cycle and won the [[run-off election]] for Place 4 on May 19, 1990. He was the first African American to be elected to the Arlington City Council.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/news/my_arlington_t_x/news_archive/2017_archived_news/may_2017/20_year_elzie_odom_reflects_on_his_arlington_dream|title=20 YEARS AFTER BEING ELECTED, FORMER MAYOR ELZIE ODOM REFLECTS ON HIS ARLINGTON DREAM|last=Office of Communication|first=|date=May 18, 2017|website=Arlington|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> While he was a member of the city council, he worked on transportation, mobility, and redistricting issues facing Arlington.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arlingtontx.gov/residents/about_arlington/history_of_arlington/hall_of_mayors/elzie_odom|title=ELZIE ODOM|last=City of Arlington|first=|date=|website=Arlington|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Odom and the city council increased minority representation on Arlington's boards and commissions, mirroring the city's population. In 1990, only two members of city boards and commissions were [[Person of color|people of color]]. By 1996, 22% of members of Arlington's boards and commissions were people of color.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Garcia|first=Eric|url=|title=City panels reflect minority numbers - Report shows that council's appointees are about proportionate to city's population - members say they want to increase minority representation|date=April 24, 1996|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> While in office, he served as president of the Arlington Sport Facilities Development Authority, oversaw construction of [[The Ballpark In Arlington|The Ballpark in Arlington]], and chaired the Arlington City Council's Youth Activities, Waste Water Treatment, Garbage Disposal, Community Development, and Employee Benefits committees. He also represented the city of Arlington on the [[North Central Texas Council of Governments]], the Tarrant County Housing Partnership, the Texas Municipal League, the Working Connection, and the State Attorney General's Municipal Advisory Committee.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Cole|first=Earnestine|url=|title=Council Member Odom Runs for Mayor of Arlington|date=March 26, 1997|work=La Vida News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> During his tenure, the council successfully kept [[General Motors]]' [[Arlington Assembly]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Worcester|first=Lea|title=Legendary Locals of Arlington, Texas|last2=Barker|first2=Evelyn|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-1-4671-0058-8|location=|pages=29}}</ref> and the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in Arlington.<ref name=\":3\" />   \n\n== Arlington mayor ==\nMayor [https://www.arlingtontx.gov/residents/about_arlington/history_of_arlington/hall_of_mayors/richard_greene Richard Greene] had served in office for a decade when he announced that he would not be seeking reelection in 1997. Odom did not immediately seek to run for office as Mayor of Arlington as he did not want to risk losing his District 1 single-member council seat,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Accessible and Approachable|last=Doclar|first=Mary|date=May 11, 1997|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram, The Weekly Review|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and it was not until he was inspired by a sermon at his church that he decided to run for mayor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Mayor-Elect Reflects on Historic Victory: Odom sees God as Key to Triumph|date=May 5, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 1997, Odom announced his plans to run for office. He stated that his reason for running was: \"because I care for my family, my city, and its people, I am running for Mayor of the greatest city in the world. I plan to run a clean and positive neighbor-to-neighbor campaign with a simple theme: Getting Results For Arlington.\" Odom outlined a 10-point plan for his future administration, which included improving traffic and mobility, reducing crime, encouraging public-private partnerships, addressing unnecessary spending, and economic development.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Council member Odom Runs for Mayor of Arlington|last=|first=|date=March 26, 1997|work=La Vida News: The Black Voice|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He received endorsements from council members and Arlington businesses.<ref name=\":2\" /> Odom won the election with 8,752 votes. His closest challenger was Laura Hightower, who won 7,060 votes.<ref name=\":0\" /> He and Hightower received 50.19% and 40.49% of the votes, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=It's Odom's Character, Supporters Say|last=Lee|first=Renee C.|date=May 11, 1997|work=Arlington Star-Telegram|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> City officials had estimated a voter turnout rate of 7.4%, but it reached 10%,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=10-percent Turnout Highest in a Decade|last=|first=|date=May 4, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> the highest in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rankin|first=Jennifer|url=|title=Turnout breaks 10-year high, officials say|date=May 4, 1997|work=Arlington Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhile in office, Odom advocated for Arlington youth, inviting students to visit his office during winter break. He also supported programs for citizens with disabilities and seniors. During this time, Arlington taxpayers paid off The Ballpark in Arlington years ahead of the payment cutoff date, and the city created a street maintenance sales program. He retired in 2003.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2001 Arlington mayoral election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odom, Elzie}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Arlington, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas city council members]]\n[[Category:School board members in Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Newton County, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Orange, Texas]]\n[[Category:Prairie View A&M University alumni]]\n[[Category:NAACP activists]]\n[[Category:United States Postal Service people]]\n", "name_user": "Michael Barera", "label": "safe", "comment": "Creating a top-level \"political career\" heading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elzie_Odom"}
{"title_page": "Secret Combination (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Secret Combination\n| cover      = Kalomoira-Secret_Combination(2008).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kalomoira]]\n| album      = [[Secret Combination the Album|Secret Combination]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2008|02|06}}\n| format     =\n*Radio single\n*digital download\n*[[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2007\u20132008\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[La\u00efko|La\u00efko-pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:00\n| label      =\n*[[Heaven Music]]\n*Catchy Tunes\n| writer     =\n*Poseidonas Giannopoulos\n*Konstadinos Pantzis\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Gine Mazi Mou Paidi]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Please Don't Break My Heart]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       =\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = [[Image:Secret Combination(cover 2).jpg|200px]]\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Eurovision Promotional Cover\n}}\n{{Infobox song contest entry | embed=yes\n| song = {{flagicon|Greece}} \"Secret Combination\"\n| image = \n| caption = \n| year = 2008\n| country = Greece\n| artist = [[Kalomira]]\n| as =\n| with =\n| language = English\n| languages =\n| composer = Konstantinos Pantzis\n| lyricist = Poseidonas Giannopoulos\n| conductor =\n| place = 3rd\n| points = 218\n| place_semi = 1st\n| points_semi = 156\n| clip =\n| prev = Yassou Maria\n| prev_link = Yassou Maria\n| next = This Is Our Night\n| next_link = This Is Our Night\n}}\n}}\n\n'''\"Secret Combination\"''' is a song recorded by [[Greek American]] singer [[Kalomira]]. The song was written by Poseidonas Giannopoulos and Konstadinos Pantzis. It is best known as the [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Greek entry]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]], held in [[Belgrade]].\n\nIt was the first single released from Kalomira's fourth studio album titled ''[[Secret Combination the Album]]''. It earned third place in the Eurovision final, finishing behind [[Russia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Russia]] and [[Ukraine in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Ukraine]], despite leading early in the final vote. Since the contest, the song has become a successful hit throughout [[Europe]] peaking at #1 in [[Greece]] and [[Cyprus]], and reaching the top 40 singles in [[Turkey]], [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]] and [[Finland]]'s download chart, all achieved as a result of digital sales alone. It also charted in [[Belgium]], [[Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]], and [[Canada]].\n\n== Background and composition ==\n\"Secret Combination\" was officially released to the media and radio stations by [[Ellinik\u00ed Radiofon\u00eda Tile\u00f3rasi|ERT]] on 6 February 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=1883|title=GREECE - ERT announes date and venue for national final|date=21 December 2007|website=OikoTimes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721154702/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=1883|archive-date=21 July 2011|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>{{Better source|date=May 2016}} The song was Kalomira's entry in a [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|three way race]] to be Greece's entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]]. She battled both [[Chrispa]] and [[Kostas Martakis]] for the spot. The final decision was made on February 27, 2008 - Kalomira won, and after competing in the semi-final on 20 May 2008 she represented Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest final on 24 May in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]. Her song was performed 21st out of 25. Her and Kostas Martakis's songs were leaked onto the internet on February 3, three days before the official release, although the leaked versions were uncompleted demos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2427|title=GREECE - Two national final songs leaked on the web|date=3 February 2008|website=Oiko Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053044/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2427|archive-date=10 February 2012|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> The song was released as a digital download on 12 February 2008 and a CD single on 28 March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0397 \u039a\u0391\u039b\u039f\u039c\u039f\u0399\u03a1\u0391 \u0395\u039a\u03a0\u03a1\u039f\u03a3\u03a9\u03a0\u039f\u03a3 \u03a4\u0397\u03a3 \u0395\u039b\u039b\u0391\u0394\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a4\u0397 EUROVISION 2008 |url=http://www.heavenmusic.gr/articleDetail/0,3702,175802,00.html |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303232427/http://www.heavenmusic.gr:80/articleDetail/0,3702,175802,00.html |archivedate=3 March 2008|accessdate=28 March 2008|publisher=[[Heaven Music]]}}</ref> Kalomira has stated that she plans to record a Greek-language version of \"Secret Combination\" after the contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/11183/greece_ogae_serbia_welcomes_kalomira/|title=Eurovision Greece: OGAE Serbia welcomes Kalomira|last=Djelic|first=Velimir|date=22 April 2008|website=Eurovision News, Polls and Information by esctoday|language=en-US|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Music video and promotion ==\nThe shooting lasted nearly twenty consecutive hours, and it was exhausting for [[Kalomira]] and for the team that worked under the guidance of director Kostas Kapetanidis.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://eurovision.ert.gr/el/nea/etoimo-to-videoclip.htm|title=\u0388\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf videoclip! - Eurovision Greece 2008|language=el|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318222049/http://eurovision.ert.gr/el/nea/etoimo-to-videoclip.htm|archive-date=18 March 2008|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> The director decided to focus on the face of the young performer and so chose to do the shoot in a studio and not outdoors. Sometimes alone, sometimes flanked by dancers, Kalomira danced and sang while wearing clothes selected from the collection of [[J.Lo]] by [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In some scenes of the video, impressive objects with bright colors such as a red [[Ducati]] motor bike, a huge [[disco ball]], and big letters with the title of the song were used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4T44asjIbmg|title=Kalomoira - SECRET COMBINATION|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|publisher=|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> The choreography was by Svitailof Ivan and the styling was George Segredaki and Constantine Koutsomichou while the hair and make-up were overseen by Dimitris Giannetos.<ref name=\":1\" /> Through the video clip, Kalomira reveals another side of: sexy, feminine, charming but always innocent and sweet in a quick clip of the montage. In the video edition, the song has changed a lot. On 14 March 2008, [[New Hellenic Television|NET]] exclusively aired the official Eurovision video clip of Secret combination during their evening news at 20:00 [[Central European Time|CET]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10869|title=Eurovision Song Contest Serbia 2008 {{!}} News - Greece: [UPD] Official Eurovision video aired tonight|last=Floras|first=Stella|date=14 March 2008|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315153101/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10869|archive-date=15 March 2008|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> International fans were able to watch through a satellite broadcast on [[ERT World]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Critical reaction to the song was mostly positive.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Reception and chart performance==\nCritical reaction to the song was mostly positive, with the entertainment reporter from [[BBC News]] Michael Osborn describing it as \"a perky pop song with a definite Greek flavour.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7376968.stm#10 |title=Eurovision vote 2008: Top 10 |work= [[BBC News]] |date=25 May 2008|accessdate=29 May 2008}}</ref> The British LGR radio station described the song as a \"infectiously catchy, ethno R&B song\" and it stayed 6 weeks in radio's Top 20 Chart.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nThe popularity of the single leading up to the ''Eurovision Song Contest'', and the positive critical reception received, ensured the commercial success of \"''Secret Combination''\" as a CD and radio single in [[Greece]] and [[Cyprus]]. The song topped the Greek Singles Chart and Digital Singles Chart for two weeks, before being knocked-off by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\u2019s and [[Justin Timberlake]]\u2019s \"''[[4 Minutes (Madonna song)|4 Minutes]]''\" to second place.\n\nElsewhere, \"''Secret Combination''\" was released solely as a digital download from 26 February 2008 , where the song became fairly successful in [[Europe]] considering it was never released physically nor to radio stations.\n\nOn national charts, \"''Secret Combination''\" peaked in the Finish Download Chart at #29 and entered many European singles charts, despite not having a physical release in those countries, thus charting on downloads alone. On 29 May 2008 the song debuted at #50 in the Swedish Top 60 Chart and peaked at #38 the following week. Additionally, on 30 May 2008 the song debuted at #29 on the Danish Singles Top 40 and in the [[Irish Singles Chart]] at #46. In the [[United Kingdom]], the song debuted on the midweek chart at #33 but by 2 June 2008 had reached #71 in the week-end chart. Elsewhere in Europe, the song peaked  at #18 in [[Turkey]]\u2019s ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top 20 Chart, at #19 in the Belgian ''Ultratip'' Chart due to digital sales and airplay (specifically, in [[Flanders]]).\n\n== Eurovision ==\n{{main|Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008}}\n=== National Final ===\nKalomira appeared on stage in a short [[J-Lo]] dress,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2538|title=GREECE - Kalomira (NF, 2008) in New York for J LO clothes|last=Konstantopoulos|first=Fotis|date=11 February 2008|website=Oiko Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053311/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2538|archive-date=10 February 2012|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> accompanied by four male back up dancers, two of which had appeared with [[Elena Paparizou]] in [[Kiev]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005]]. At the start of the show, the four dancers hold her up on top of themselves, while she is lying down. Later she comes down, and starts dancing with them. Each of the dancers has a letter painted under their undershirts and at the end of the song, they stand next to each other spelling the word \"love\". Kalomira won the National Final with 167,000 votes and for the first time in number of years, the media didn't doubt the result of the selection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2745 |title=GREECE - High TV rates in Greece, poor televoting figures |date=28 February 2008 |website=Oiko Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053302/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2745 |archive-date=February 10, 2012 |access-date=1 May 2016|url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n=== Semi-final ===\n[[Kalomira]] was scheduled to presented \"Secret Combination\" 19th (last) in the first semi-final on 20 May 2008. Konstantinos Pantzis, the composer, announced that there would be a few tweaks to the song for its appearance at Eurovision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurovision-greece.com/news/2008/March/news13.html |title=\u0397 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ad\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 Secret combination |date=13 March 2008 |website=Eurovision-Greece |language=el |trans-title=The new version of Secret Combination |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210062752/http://www.eurovision-greece.com/news/2008/March/news13.html |archive-date=10 February 2012 |access-date=1 May 2016|url-status=unfit }}</ref> The changes included a new beat to the introduction and a few changes to the chorus. [[Ellinik\u00ed Radiofon\u00eda Tile\u00f3rasi|ERT]] announced that this new version would be presented to the [[European Broadcasting Union]] as the official version of the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10856?|title=News - Greece: Eurovision Version of Secret Combination|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=13 March 2008|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001214118/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10856?|archive-date=1 October 2008|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKalomira performed 19th, the last act of the night. The stage show included new choreography, as well as Victoria Halkiti and Nektarios Georgiadis as backing vocalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lgr.co.uk/music/news/12899/kalomoira-hails-3rd-in-eurovision-well-done-to-greece/|title=Greece: THIRD in Eurovision! Well done to Kalomoira!|last=Neophytou|first=Tony|date=14 May 2008|website=London Greek Radio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530160522/http://lgr.co.uk/music/news/12899/kalomoira-hails-3rd-in-eurovision-well-done-to-greece/|archive-date=30 May 2008}}</ref> There was also a large book on stage that Kalomira stepped out of when singing the lyrics \"an open book\". At the same moment, [[Kalomira]] changed her outfit converting it from a pink dress into a mini-silver skirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10687|title=Tonight live: Greece decides Eurovision entry|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=27 February 2008|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403034836/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10687|archive-date=3 April 2012|accessdate=8 August 2008}}</ref> She wore clothes exclusively by [[J-Lo]] and managed to finish first receiving 156 points.\n\n=== Final ===\n[[File:ESC 2008 - Greece - Kalomira, 1st semifinal.jpg|thumb|Kalomira performing \"Secret Combination\" at the Eurovision final.]]\nKalomira performed a repeat of her semi-final performance at the Eurovision Final held on 24 May 2008. She presented \"Secret Combination\" 21st on the night after [[Azerbaijan]] and before [[Spain]]. Having led initially in the voting, Kalomira finished in third place behind Russia and Ukraine, receiving 218 points. The song received 12 points from [[United Kingdom]], [[Germany]], [[Albania]], [[San Marino]], [[Cyprus]] and [[Romania]]. On the other hand, [[Latvia]], [[Iceland]], [[Portugal]], [[Finland]], [[Norway]] and [[Lithuania]] were the only countries that did not vote it in their top ten, thereby giving it no points. The British LGR radio station commented \"Visually, the presentation was quite addictively enticing, with a stunningly gorgeous Kalomira, her singing/dance capabilities and her three acrobatic male dancers. The purple-heart gimmick carved out of the giant, life-sized book, proving ingenious\".<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |url=http://www.lgr.co.uk/music/news/13012/secret-combination-storms-into-uk-top-40/ |title='Secret Combination' storms into UK TOP 40 |publisher= London Greek Radio |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=29 May 2008}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Eurovision 2008 Mix) - 3:00\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Mystic Soumka Mix) - 4:06\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Electropop Mix) - 3:33\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Backing Track Mix) - 3:00\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | [[Greece]]\n| 6 February 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Radio Single]]\n|-\n| 12 February 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n| 28 March 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[CD Single]]\n|-\n| Worldwide (iTunes)\n| 26 February 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n| [[Scandinavia]]\n| 25 June 2008\n| Catchy Tunes<ref>[http://www.catchytunes.se/ Catchy Tunes<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| [[CD Single]]\n|}\n\n==Charts and certifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  | Chart (2008)\n!  | Peak\n<!-- iTUNES IS NOT AN OFFICIAL CHART, ITS JUST A RANDOM RETAILER -->\n|-\n| [[Ultratop|Belgium (Flanders) Singles Chart]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/ultratip/2008/20080614|title=Ultratip Bubbling Under - 2008-06-21|website=ultratop.be|language=nl|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n| align=center | 68\n|-\n| [[Mediabase|Canadian Airplay Chart]] <ref>[http://www.mmr247.com/mmrweb/AllAccess/Charts.asp?format=z1k&cutoff=0&showtopn=2000 Canada - Top 40] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228082512/http://www.mmr247.com/mmrweb/AllAccess/Charts.asp?format=z1k&cutoff=0&showtopn=2000 |date=28 February 2007}}</ref>\n| align=center | 331\n|-\n| [[Tracklisten|Danish Singles Chart]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Kalomira&titel=Secret+Combination&cat=s|title=Kalomira - Secret Combination|website=danishcharts.com|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n| align=center | 29\n|-\n| [[Finland|Finnish Download Chart]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.latauslista.fi/lista/2008/22 |title=Kalomira Latauslista Official Finnish Download Chart |access-date=12 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090102213229/http://latauslista.fi/lista/2008/22 |archive-date=2 January 2009|url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| align=center | 29\n|-\n| [[Greece|Greek ''Billboard'' Singles Chart]] <ref>[http://www.ifpi.gr/chart03.htm Greek Top 50 Singles] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406034909/http://www.ifpi.gr/chart03.htm |date=6 April 2007|accessdate=11 May 2008|publisher=[[IFPI]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/chart_display.jsp?g=Singles&f=Greece Billboard.com]</ref>\n| align=center | 1\n|-\n| [[Irish Singles Chart]] <ref>[http://www.irma.ie/aucharts.asp Irish Top 50] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BsGw4ATh?url=http://www.irma.ie/aucharts.asp |date=2 November 2012}}</ref>\n| align=center | 46\n|-\n| [[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Singles Chart]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Kalomira&titel=Secret+Combination&cat=s|title=Kalomira - Secret Combination|website=swedishcharts.com|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n| align=center | 38\n|-\n| [[Turkey Top 20 Chart|Turkish ''Billboard'' Singles Chart]] <ref>[http://www.billboard.com.tr/pages/Turkiye_top20.aspx Billboard T\u00fcrkiye Top 20] Accessed 12 April 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330214158/http://www.billboard.com.tr/pages/Turkiye_top20.aspx |date=30 March 2008 }}</ref>\n| align=center | 18\n|-\n| [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/4092/kalomoira/|title=KALOMOIRA \u2013 full Official Chart History|website=Official Charts Company|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n| align=center | 71\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2008}}\n\n[[Category:2008 singles]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2008]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Greece]]\n[[Category:Heaven Music singles]]\n[[Category:Kalomira songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Kostas Kapetanidis]]\n[[Category:English-language Greek songs]]\n[[Category:2008 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Secret Combination\n| cover      = Kalomoira-Secret_Combination(2008).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kalomoira]]\n| album      = [[Secret Combination the Album|Secret Combination]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2008|02|06}}\n| format     =\n*Radio single\n*digital download\n*[[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2007\u20132008\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[La\u00efko|La\u00efko-pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:00\n| label      =\n*[[Heaven Music]]\n*Catchy Tunes\n| writer     =\n*Poseidonas Giannopoulos\n*Konstadinos Pantzis\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Gine Mazi Mou Paidi]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Please Don't Break My Heart]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       =\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = [[Image:Secret Combination(cover 2).jpg|200px]]\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Eurovision Promotional Cover\n}}\n{{Infobox song contest entry | embed=yes\n| song = {{flagicon|Greece}} \"Secret Combination\"\n| image = \n| caption = \n| year = 2008\n| country = Greece\n| artist = [[Kalomira]]\n| as =\n| with =\n| language = English\n| languages =\n| composer = Konstantinos Pantzis\n| lyricist = Poseidonas Giannopoulos\n| conductor =\n| place = 3rd\n| points = 218\n| place_semi = 1st\n| points_semi = 156\n| clip =\n| prev = Yassou Maria\n| prev_link = Yassou Maria\n| next = This Is Our Night\n| next_link = This Is Our Night\n}}\n}}\n\n'''\"Secret Combination\"''' is a song recorded by [[Greek American]] singer [[Kalomira]]. The song was written by Poseidonas Giannopoulos and Konstadinos Pantzis. It is best known as the [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Greek entry]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]], held in [[Belgrade]].\n\nIt was the first single released from Kalomira's fourth studio album titled ''[[Secret Combination the Album]]''. It earned third place in the Eurovision final, finishing behind [[Russia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Russia]] and [[Ukraine in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Ukraine]], despite leading early in the final vote. Since the contest, the song has become a successful hit throughout [[Europe]] peaking at #1 in [[Greece]] and [[Cyprus]], and reaching the top 40 singles in [[Turkey]], [[Denmark]], [[Sweden]] and [[Finland]]'s download chart, all achieved as a result of digital sales alone. It also charted in [[Belgium]], [[Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]], and [[Canada]].\n\n== Background and composition ==\n\"Secret Combination\" was officially released to the media and radio stations by [[Ellinik\u00ed Radiofon\u00eda Tile\u00f3rasi|ERT]] on February 6, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=1883|title=GREECE - ERT announes date and venue for national final|date=2007-12-21|website=Oiko Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721154702/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=1883|archive-date=2011-07-21|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref>{{Better source|date=May 2016}} The song was Kalomira's entry in a [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|three way race]] to be Greece's entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]]. She battled both [[Chrispa]] and [[Kostas Martakis]] for the spot. The final decision was made on February 27, 2008 - Kalomira won, and after competing in the semi-final on 20 May 2008 she represented Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest final on 24 May in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]. Her song was performed 21st out of 25. Her and Kostas Martakis's songs were leaked onto the internet on February 3, three days before the official release, although the leaked versions were uncompleted demos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2427|title=GREECE - Two national final songs leaked on the web|date=2008-02-03|website=Oiko Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053044/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2427|archive-date=2012-02-10|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref> The song was released as a digital download on February 12, 2008 and a CD single on March 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0397 \u039a\u0391\u039b\u039f\u039c\u039f\u0399\u03a1\u0391 \u0395\u039a\u03a0\u03a1\u039f\u03a3\u03a9\u03a0\u039f\u03a3 \u03a4\u0397\u03a3 \u0395\u039b\u039b\u0391\u0394\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a4\u0397 EUROVISION 2008 |url=http://www.heavenmusic.gr/articleDetail/0,3702,175802,00.html |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303232427/http://www.heavenmusic.gr:80/articleDetail/0,3702,175802,00.html |archivedate=2008-03-03 }} ''[[Heaven Music]]''. Retrieved on March 28, 2008.</ref> Kalomira has stated that she plans to record a Greek-language version of \"Secret Combination\" after the contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/11183/greece_ogae_serbia_welcomes_kalomira/|title=Eurovision Greece: OGAE Serbia welcomes Kalomira|last=Djelic|first=Velimir|date=2008-04-22|website=Eurovision News, Polls and Information by esctoday|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== Music video and promotion ==\nThe shooting lasted nearly twenty consecutive hours, and it was exhausting for [[Kalomira]] and for the team that worked under the guidance of director Kostas Kapetanidis.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://eurovision.ert.gr/el/nea/etoimo-to-videoclip.htm|title=\u0388\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf videoclip! - Eurovision Greece 2008|language=el|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318222049/http://eurovision.ert.gr/el/nea/etoimo-to-videoclip.htm|archive-date=2008-03-18|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref> The director decided to focus on the face of the young performer and so chose to do the shoot in a studio and not outdoors. Sometimes alone, sometimes flanked by dancers, Kalomira danced and sang while wearing clothes selected from the collection of [[J.Lo]] by [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In some scenes of the video, impressive objects with bright colors such as a red [[Ducati]] motor bike, a huge [[disco ball]], and big letters with the title of the song were used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4T44asjIbmg|title=Kalomoira - SECRET COMBINATION|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|publisher=|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref> The choreography was by Svitailof Ivan and the styling was George Segredaki and Constantine Koutsomichou while the hair and make-up were overseen by Dimitris Giannetos.<ref name=\":1\" /> Through the video clip, Kalomira reveals another side of: sexy, feminine, charming but always innocent and sweet in a quick clip of the montage. In the video edition, the song has changed a lot. On March 14, 2008, [[New Hellenic Television|NET]] exclusively aired the official Eurovision video clip of Secret combination during their evening news at 20:00 [[Central European Time|CET]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10869|title=Eurovision Song Contest Serbia 2008 {{!}} News - Greece: [UPD] Official Eurovision video aired tonight|last=Floras|first=Stella|date=2008-03-14|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315153101/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10869|archive-date=2008-03-15|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref> International fans were able to watch through a satellite broadcast on [[ERT World]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Critical reaction to the song was mostly positive.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Reception and chart performance==\nCritical reaction to the song was mostly positive, with the entertainment reporter from [[BBC News]] Michael Osborn describing it as \"a perky pop song with a definite Greek flavour.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7376968.stm#10 |title=Eurovision vote 2008: Top 10 |work= [[BBC News]] |date=25 May 2008|accessdate=2008-05-29}}</ref> The British LGR radio station described the song as a \"infectiously catchy, ethno R&B song\" and it stayed 6 weeks in radio's Top 20 Chart.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nThe popularity of the single leading up to the ''Eurovision Song Contest'', and the positive critical reception received, ensured the commercial success of \"''Secret Combination''\" as a CD and radio single in [[Greece]] and [[Cyprus]]. The song topped the Greek Singles Chart and Digital Singles Chart for two weeks, before being knocked-off by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\u2019s and [[Justin Timberlake]]\u2019s \"''[[4 Minutes (Madonna song)|4 Minutes]]''\" to second place.\n\nElsewhere, \"''Secret Combination''\" was released solely as a digital download from February 26, 2008 , where the song became fairly successful in [[Europe]] considering it was never released physically nor to radio stations.\n\nOn national charts, \"''Secret Combination''\" peaked in the Finish Download Chart at #29 and entered many European singles charts, despite not having a physical release in those countries, thus charting on downloads alone. On 29 May 2008 the song debuted at #50 in the Swedish Top 60 Chart and peaked at #38 the following week. Additionally, on 30 May 2008 the song debuted at #29 on the Danish Singles Top 40 and in the [[Irish Singles Chart]] at #46. In the [[United Kingdom]], the song debuted on the midweek chart at #33 but by 2 June 2008 had reached #71 in the week-end chart. Elsewhere in Europe, the song peaked  at #18 in [[Turkey]]\u2019s ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top 20 Chart, at #19 in the Belgian ''Ultratip'' Chart due to digital sales and airplay (specifically, in [[Flanders]]).\n\n== Eurovision ==\n{{main|Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008}}\n=== National Final ===\nKalomira appeared on stage in a short [[J-Lo]] dress,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2538|title=GREECE - Kalomira (NF, 2008) in New York for J LO clothes|last=Konstantopoulos|first=Fotis|date=2008-02-11|website=Oiko Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053311/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2538|archive-date=2012-02-10|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref> accompanied by four male back up dancers, two of which had appeared with [[Elena Paparizou]] in [[Kiev]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005]]. At the start of the show, the four dancers hold her up on top of themselves, while she is lying down. Later she comes down, and starts dancing with them. Each of the dancers has a letter painted under their undershirts and at the end of the song, they stand next to each other spelling the word \"love\". Kalomira won the National Final with 167,000 votes and for the first time in number of years, the media didn't doubt the result of the selection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2745 |title=GREECE - High TV rates in Greece, poor televoting figures |date=2008-02-28 |website=Oiko Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210053302/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=2745 |archive-date=February 10, 2012 |access-date=2016-05-01 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n=== Semi-final ===\n[[Kalomira]] was scheduled to presented \"Secret Combination\" 19th (last) in the first semi-final on May 20, 2008. Konstantinos Pantzis, the composer, announced that there would be a few tweaks to the song for its appearance at Eurovision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurovision-greece.com/news/2008/March/news13.html |title=\u0397 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ad\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 Secret combination |date=2008-03-13 |website=Eurovision-Greece |language=el |trans-title=The new version of Secret Combination |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210062752/http://www.eurovision-greece.com/news/2008/March/news13.html |archive-date=February 10, 2012 |access-date=2016-05-01 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> The changes included a new beat to the introduction and a few changes to the chorus. [[Ellinik\u00ed Radiofon\u00eda Tile\u00f3rasi|ERT]] announced that this new version would be presented to the [[European Broadcasting Union]] as the official version of the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10856?|title=News - Greece: Eurovision Version of Secret Combination|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=2008-03-13|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001214118/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10856?|archive-date=2008-10-01|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKalomira performed 19th, the last act of the night. The stage show included new choreography, as well as Victoria Halkiti and Nektarios Georgiadis as backing vocalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lgr.co.uk/music/news/12899/kalomoira-hails-3rd-in-eurovision-well-done-to-greece/|title=Greece: THIRD in Eurovision! Well done to Kalomoira!|last=Neophytou|first=Tony|date=2008-05-14|website=London Greek Radio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530160522/http://lgr.co.uk/music/news/12899/kalomoira-hails-3rd-in-eurovision-well-done-to-greece/|archive-date=2008-05-30}}</ref> There was also a large book on stage that Kalomira stepped out of when singing the lyrics \"an open book\". At the same moment, [[Kalomira]] changed her outfit converting it from a pink dress into a mini-silver skirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10687|title=Tonight live: Greece decides Eurovision entry|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=2008-02-27|website=ESCToday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403034836/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/10687|archive-date=2012-04-03|accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref> She wore clothes exclusively by [[J-Lo]] and managed to finish first receiving 156 points.\n\n=== Final ===\n[[File:ESC 2008 - Greece - Kalomira, 1st semifinal.jpg|thumb|Kalomira performing \"Secret Combination\" at the Eurovision final.]]\nKalomira performed a repeat of her semi-final performance at the Eurovision Final held on May 24, 2008. She presented \"Secret Combination\" 21st on the night after [[Azerbaijan]] and before [[Spain]]. Having led initially in the voting, Kalomira finished in third place behind Russia and Ukraine, receiving 218 points. The song received 12 points from [[United Kingdom]], [[Germany]], [[Albania]], [[San Marino]], [[Cyprus]] and [[Romania]]. On the other hand, [[Latvia]], [[Iceland]], [[Portugal]], [[Finland]], [[Norway]] and [[Lithuania]] were the only countries that did not vote it in their top ten, thereby giving it no points. The British LGR radio station commented \"Visually, the presentation was quite addictively enticing, with a stunningly gorgeous Kalomira, her singing/dance capabilities and her three acrobatic male dancers. The purple-heart gimmick carved out of the giant, life-sized book, proving ingenious\".<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |url=http://www.lgr.co.uk/music/news/13012/secret-combination-storms-into-uk-top-40/ |title='Secret Combination' storms into UK TOP 40 |publisher= London Greek Radio |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-29}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Eurovision 2008 Mix) - 3:00\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Mystic Soumka Mix) - 4:06\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Electropop Mix) - 3:33\n# \"Secret Combination\" (Backing Track Mix) - 3:00\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | [[Greece]]\n| February 6, 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Radio Single]]\n|-\n| February 12, 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n| March 28, 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[CD Single]]\n|-\n| Worldwide (iTunes)\n| February 26, 2008\n| [[Heaven Music|Heaven]]\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n| [[Scandinavia]]\n| June 25, 2008\n| Catchy Tunes<ref>[http://www.catchytunes.se/ Catchy Tunes<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| [[CD Single]]\n|}\n\n==Charts and certifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  | Chart (2008)\n!  | Peak\n<!-- iTUNES IS NOT AN OFFICIAL CHART, ITS JUST A RANDOM RETAILER -->\n|-\n| [[Ultratop|Belgium (Flanders) Singles Chart]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/ultratip/2008/20080614|title=Ultratip Bubbling Under - 2008-06-21|website=ultratop.be|language=nl|access-date=2016-05-01}}</ref>\n| align=center | 68\n|-\n| [[Mediabase|Canadian Airplay Chart]] <ref>[http://www.mmr247.com/mmrweb/AllAccess/Charts.asp?format=z1k&cutoff=0&showtopn=2000 Canada - Top 40] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228082512/http://www.mmr247.com/mmrweb/AllAccess/C